    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>If the Shoe Doesn't Fit, Why Wear It?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Art Grillo says excoriating women's shoe industry for its misogyny is tired argument; holds professional women wear high heels to be taller and thus more impressive</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Excoriating the women's shoe industry for its misogyny is a tired argument (Op-Ed, Oct. 18).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Excoriating the women's shoe industry for its misogyny is a tired argument (Op-Ed, Oct. 18).</p>
        <p>Is it really just one industry's sexism that compels female lawyers at an international conference, women we might expect to feel proud and self-assured, to wear painful, debilitating footware? Or is it a lawyerly need to dress as uncomfortably as possible to achieve some aura of power and respectability?</p>
        <p>High heels make a lawyer taller and thus more impressive, just as  a buttoned collar and a tightly knotted tie reassure us that the wearer values conformance over self-expression.</p>
        <p>ART GRILLO  Berkeley, Calif., Oct. 18, 2000</p>
      </block>
